# Tech Stack Rules

## React (v18.3)

This is a client-side SPA (not Next.js). No Server Components, no SSR.

### Component Declaration

Use arrow functions with default export. This is the established pattern in this project.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Arrow function component with default export
const GameResult = ({ gameState, initGame }: Props) => {
  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>
}

export default GameResult

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Named export or function declaration (inconsistent with project)
export function GameResult({ gameState, initGame }: Props) {
  return <div>{/* ... */}</div>
}
```

### Hooks

- Use `useCallback` for functions passed as props or used in dependency arrays
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computations or derived data
- Use `useState` for local UI state only

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Memoized handler passed to child
const handleNextStep = useCallback(() => {
  setStep(prev => prev + 1)
}, [])

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Inline function re-created every render
const handleNextStep = () => {
  setStep(prev => prev + 1)
}
// ...passed as <Child onNext={handleNextStep} />
```

## TanStack React Query (v5.74)

Server state is managed exclusively through React Query. Do not use useState for data fetched from Firebase.

### Query Key Convention

Use SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE string arrays for query keys. See @src/api/firebaseApi.ts for the established pattern.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Descriptive query key with parameter
queryKey: ['GAME_CONTENT', sortBy]

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Vague or unscoped query key
queryKey: ['data']
```

### Query Hook Pattern

All Firebase query hooks are co-located in `src/api/firebaseApi.ts`. Each hook wraps `useQuery` or `useMutation` and returns the React Query result directly.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Typed query with proper enabled guard
export const useMyRankInfo = (myId: string | null) => {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['MY_RANK_INFO', myId],
    queryFn: async () => {
      if (!myId) return null
      // ...fetch logic
    },
    enabled: !!myId,
  })
}

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Query without enabled guard when parameter can be null
export const useMyRankInfo = (myId: string | null) => {
  return useQuery({
    queryKey: ['MY_RANK_INFO', myId],
    queryFn: async () => {
      const docSnap = await getDoc(doc(db, 'contents', myId!)) // dangerous !
    },
  })
}
```

### Mutation Pattern

Mutations must have `onError` handler. Use `queryClient.invalidateQueries` in `onSuccess` to sync cache.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Mutation with error handling and cache invalidation
export const useReactToContent = () => {
  const queryClient = useQueryClient()
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: async (params: TReactionParams) => { /* ... */ },
    onSuccess: () => queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['GAME_CONTENT'] }),
    onError: (error: Error) => alert(error.message ?? 'An error occurred.'),
  })
}

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî No onError, no cache invalidation
export const useReactToContent = () => {
  return useMutation({
    mutationFn: async (params: TReactionParams) => { /* ... */ },
  })
}
```

### QueryClient Configuration

QueryClient is instantiated in `App.tsx` with these defaults ‚Äî maintain consistency:
- `refetchOnWindowFocus: false`
- `staleTime: 60 * 1000 * 10` (10 minutes)
- `retry: 1`

## Firebase (v11.3 ‚Äî Modular SDK)

Use the modular (tree-shakeable) import style. Never use compat imports.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Modular import
import { collection, getDocs, query, orderBy, limit } from 'firebase/firestore'

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Compat import
import firebase from 'firebase/compat/app'
import 'firebase/compat/firestore'
```

### Firestore Operations

All Firestore operations go through `src/api/firebaseApi.ts`, using the `db` instance from @src/firebase/firebaseClient.ts.

- Use `setDoc` with explicit document ID for writes
- Use `serverTimestamp()` for date fields
- Use `increment()` for atomic counter updates
- Use `getCountFromServer` for count queries (avoids reading all documents)

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Atomic increment with server-side operation
await updateDoc(contentRef, {
  [`reactions.${reaction}`]: increment(1),
  reactionTotal: increment(1),
})

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Client-side read-then-write (race condition)
const snap = await getDoc(contentRef)
const current = snap.data().reactionTotal
await updateDoc(contentRef, { reactionTotal: current + 1 })
```

### Firebase Config

All Firebase config values come from Vite environment variables (`import.meta.env.VITE_*`). Never hardcode credentials.

## React Router DOM (v6.27)

### Routing Structure

Routes are defined in @src/shared/Router.tsx using `<BrowserRouter>` + `<Routes>` + `<Route>`.

### Lazy Loading

Non-critical pages use `React.lazy()` with `<Suspense fallback={<LottieLoading />}>`.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Lazy load for non-initial routes
const Content = lazy(() => import('../page/Content'))
const Rank = lazy(() => import('../page/Rank'))

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Eager import for rarely visited page
import SpecialThanks from '../page/SpecialThanks'
```

### Navigation Guard

Use `useNavigate()` in `useEffect` and `<Navigate>` component for auth guards.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Guard pattern used in this project
useEffect(() => {
  if (!nickname || !uniqueId) {
    navigate('/')
    return
  }
}, [navigate, nickname, uniqueId])

if (!nickname || !uniqueId) return <Navigate to="/" />
```

## React Hook Form (v7.54)

Use `react-hook-form` for all form state. No Yup/Zod schema library is installed ‚Äî use inline validation rules.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî react-hook-form with register and inline validation
const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm<TFormValues>()

<input {...register('nickname', { required: true, maxLength: 10 })} />
{errors.nickname && <span>Required</span>}

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Manual controlled input state
const [nickname, setNickname] = useState('')
const handleChange = (e) => setNickname(e.target.value)
```

## TailwindCSS (v3.4) + tailwind-merge

### Custom Theme

This project defines custom colors and fonts in @tailwind.config.js. Use the semantic color names:

| Token | Value | Usage |
|-------|-------|-------|
| `main1` | `#FCEF8D` | Primary yellow |
| `main2` | `#5B5BEC` | Primary purple |
| `main3` | `#EA6262` | Primary red / accent |
| `gray1` | `#5E5565` | Dark gray |
| `gray2` | `#AEA7B3` | Medium gray |
| `gray3` | `#D6CFDA` | Light gray |
| `font` | `#1F102A` | Text color |

Custom fonts: `font-galmuri11`, `font-galmuri9`
Custom breakpoints: `xxs: 310px`, `xs: 380px`

### Class Merging

Use `twMerge()` from `tailwind-merge` when conditionally combining Tailwind classes. Import from `tailwind-merge`.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî twMerge for conditional classes
import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge'
<p className={twMerge('text-4xl text-white', isGameRunning && 'animate-bounce')}>

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî String concatenation (may produce conflicting classes)
<p className={`text-4xl text-white ${isGameRunning ? 'animate-bounce' : ''}`}>
```

## Lottie React (v2.4)

Use `lottie-react` for JSON-based animations. Import animation data from `src/assets/lottie/`.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ
import Lottie from 'lottie-react'
import loading from '../assets/lottie/loading.json'

<Lottie animationData={loading} loop={true} />

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Using raw <video> or GIF for animations that should be Lottie
<video src="/loading.mp4" autoPlay loop />
```

## Remixicon (v4.5)

Import the CSS globally once. Use `<i>` tags with `ri-*` class names.

```tsx
// Good ‚úÖ ‚Äî Already imported globally in App.tsx
import 'remixicon/fonts/remixicon.css'
<i className="ri-arrow-left-line" />

// Bad ‚ùå ‚Äî Individual SVG imports for icons that exist in Remixicon
import ArrowLeft from './icons/arrow-left.svg'
```
